  <div class="sec-eye en">Marginalia</div><div class="sec-eye zh" style="display:none">书边笔记</div>
  <h1 class="sec-h1 en">Reading Notes</h1><h1 class="sec-h1 zh" style="display:none">读书笔记</h1>
  <div class="sec-rule"></div>
  <p class="tarot-intro en">In an era where algorithms and generative models are constantly reshaping the landscape, this feeling is becoming increasingly profound for computer researchers. LLMs are getting better and better at completing language tasks, capable of generating fluent, complete, and even touching text in an instant - as if expression itself no longer requires the accumulation of experience, time, and suffering. It seems that words are gradually detaching from the human body and existing independently. But does it truly understand those themes that recur in the present and throughout human history - the tension between idealism and reality, the entanglement of love and loss, the loneliness and struggle of the individual in the world? When a model writes about "pain", has it ever experienced pain? When it describes "meaning", has it truly questioned meaning? No, it merely highly fits the expression patterns in vast amounts of text, possessing the form of language but not necessarily touching the essence of the words themselves. 
<br><br>I have always been deeply impressed by the fact that words serve as a link that transcends time and creates a resonance between people. Especially in recent years, I have been trapped in a certain sense of emptiness - meaning has loosened, many things that were once firmly believed have begun to lose their support, problems keep emerging, but it is difficult to point to clear answers. In this situation, as an individual, I am forced to confront a more fundamental truth: the world itself does not provide meaning. When the former philosophy of existence collapsed, new meaning needed to be constructed. But "construction" is not easy; it means making choices, and making choices inherently involves uncertainty and costs. However, reading presents a different dimension: the predicament, anxiety, and pain I have experienced are not isolated exceptions. Over the past several thousand years, countless people have also stood at similar boundaries, thinking, struggling, and making choices. They wrote these experiences into books, allowing later generations to recognize their own reflections in others' words. Reading is when one throws pain into the void, and those most outstanding humans respond to you through thousands of books: I hear you, your pain is valid. This is different from "forcing oneself to say愁" (expressing sorrow artificially). Perhaps my shallow life experience is insufficient to support my acceptance of the universal sorrow of humanity， but this is not the trap of nihilism. Maybe the words themselves have no meaning， or perhaps there was no fluctuation when reading initially， but as experience accumulates gradually， those once silent words will reveal their original weight at a certain moment.</p>
  <p class="tarot-intro zh" style="display:none">在算法与生成模型不断重塑的时代，作为计算机研究者这种感觉越发深刻，大语言模型越来越好的完成语言任务，可以在瞬间生成流畅、完整、甚至动人的文字——仿佛表达本身，已不再需要经历、时间与痛苦的沉淀，文字似乎正逐渐脱离“人”的身体而独立存在。可是它是否真正理解那些在当下甚至是在人类历史中反复出现的主题——理想主义与现实的张力，爱与失去的反复纠缠，个体在世界中的孤独与挣扎？当一个模型写下“痛苦”时，它是否经历过痛苦；当它描述“意义”时，它是否真正追问过意义？不，它只是高度拟合了海量文本中的表达方式，拥有语言的形式，却未必触及文字本身。
<br><br>
我始终震撼于文字作为人与人之间跨越时间的共鸣的链接。尤其是近些年，我困于某种程度的虚无——意义变得松动，很多曾经坚信的东西开始失去支撑，问题不断出现，却很难指向清晰的答案。在这种处境下，我作为个体被迫直面一个更根本的事实：世界本身并不提供意义，当曾经的生存哲学崩塌后，新的意义需要被建构。但“建构”并不轻松，它意味着选择，而选择本身就伴随着不确定与代价。然而阅读呈现出一种不同的维度：我所经历的困境、焦虑与痛苦，并非孤立的例外。在过去几千年里，无数人也曾站在类似的边界上思考、挣扎、选择。他们把这些经验写进书中，让后来者得以在他人的文字中，辨认出自己的影子。阅读就是当人向虚空抛出痛苦时，那些最优秀的人类通过成千上万本书籍回应你：我听见了，你的痛苦成立。这不同于“为赋新词强说愁”，或许我浅薄的生命阅历不足以支撑我接纳人类的万古同悲，但这并不是虚无主义的陷阱。也许文字本身毫无意义，也许初读时并无波动，但当经验逐渐累积，那些曾经沉默的文字，会在某一刻显现出它原本的重量。</p>
